{"award_age":66.0,"bio_image":"full\/9119312e704b6987da8ccbcd61fe67d3a02262f4.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United Kingdom","date_of_birth":"1941-01-01T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/8\/83\/Martin_Evans_Nobel_Prize.jpg\/220px-Martin_Evans_Nobel_Prize.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Martin_Evans","mini_bio":"<p><b>Sir Martin John Evans<\/b> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Royal_Society\" title=\"Royal Society\">FRS<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/FMedSci\" title=\"FMedSci\" class=\"mw-redirect\">FMedSci<\/a> (b. 1 January 1941, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Stroud\" title=\"Stroud\">Stroud<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Gloucestershire\" title=\"Gloucestershire\">Gloucestershire<\/a><sup id=\"cite_ref-BBC_knighted_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Martin_Evans#cite_note-BBC_knighted-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup>) is a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Welsh_people\" title=\"Welsh people\">Welsh<\/a> biologist who, with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Matthew_Kaufman\" title=\"Matthew Kaufman\">Matthew Kaufman<\/a>, was the first to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cell_culture\" title=\"Cell culture\">culture<\/a> mice <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Embryonic_stem_cell\" title=\"Embryonic stem cell\">embryonic stem cells<\/a> and cultivate them in a laboratory in 1981. He is also known, along with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mario_Capecchi\" title=\"Mario Capecchi\">Mario Capecchi<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Oliver_Smithies\" title=\"Oliver Smithies\">Oliver Smithies<\/a>, for his work in the development of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Knockout_mouse\" title=\"Knockout mouse\">knockout mouse<\/a> and the related technology of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Gene_targeting\" title=\"Gene targeting\">gene targeting<\/a>, a method of using embryonic stem cells to create specific gene modifications in mice.<sup id=\"cite_ref-BBC_knighted_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Martin_Evans#cite_note-BBC_knighted-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-cultural_mouse_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Martin_Evans#cite_note-cultural_mouse-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> In 2007, the three shared the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> in recognition of their discovery and contribution to the efforts to develop new treatments for illnesses in humans.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Nobel_2007_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Martin_Evans#cite_note-Nobel_2007-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-DIDiscs_ME_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Martin_Evans#cite_note-DIDiscs_ME-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>He won a major scholarship to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Christ%27s_College,_Cambridge\" title=\"Christ's College, Cambridge\">Christ's College<\/a>, University of Cambridge at a time when advances in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Genetics\" title=\"Genetics\">genetics<\/a> were occurring there and became interested in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biology\" title=\"Biology\">biology<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biochemistry\" title=\"Biochemistry\">biochemistry<\/a>. He then went to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_College_London\" title=\"University College London\">University College London<\/a> where he learned laboratory skills under Dr Elizabeth Deuchar. In 1978, he moved to the Department of Genetics, at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Cambridge\" title=\"University of Cambridge\">University of Cambridge<\/a>, and in 1980 began his collaboration with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Matthew_Kaufman\" title=\"Matthew Kaufman\">Matthew Kaufman<\/a>. They explored the method of using <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Blastocysts\" title=\"Blastocysts\" class=\"mw-redirect\">blastocysts<\/a> for the isolation of embryonic stem cells. After Kaufman left, Evans continued his work, upgrading his laboratory skills to the newest technologies, isolated the embryonic stem cell of the early mouse embryo and established it in a cell culture. He genetically modified and implanted it into adult female mice with the intent of creating genetically modified offspring, work for which he was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Prize\">Nobel Prize<\/a> in 2007. Today, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Genetically_modified\" title=\"Genetically modified\" class=\"mw-redirect\">genetically modified<\/a> mice are considered vital for medical research.<\/p>","name":"Sir Martin J. Evans","place_of_birth":"Stroud ,  Gloucestershire ,  England","place_of_death":null,"text":"Sir Martin J. Evans , Physiology or Medicine, 2007","year":2007.0}